During the far warmer Eemian interglacial -- the warm phase just before the Holocene, in the current Ice Age -- polar bears may not have had any sea ice to speak of. The Eemian was thought to have been as much as +5C warmer than today's "scorching" temperatures. And that temperature went on for hundreds of years. A few thousand years were spent at least as warm as today and much of it far warmer. There is evidence off the coast of one lone island north of Europe that it experienced cold climate like today, but that was isolated. Greenland saw massive melting throughout the Eemian. Polar bears survived just fine.

We live in an Ice Age. Life does very poorly in the cold. Just look at the population gradient from poles to equator. Hi Rod, thank you for your comment however we do need to clear up a few inaccuracies and missed points within your post. One of the most common myths about polar bears is that their population numbers are overall increasing. Pre-1970‚Äôs we had very little scientifically reliable polar bear population estimates, little more than educated guesses. We can begin to quantify population number increases during the 1970‚Äôs due to the implementation of hunting regulations. As expected this helped increase the polar bear numbers within these populations. Now we can monitor populations more reliably due to advances in technology, we can see static or downward trends in almost every subpopulation within the arctic. As explained by Dr Gavin Schmidt in the film, we are very aware that our climate changes naturally over hundreds of millions of years. The important fact (that more than 97% of climate scientists agree with) is that we are causing and experiencing rapid unusual changes to our climate system. The pace of this change is greater than any ecosystem can evolutionarily adapt to (including humans). Polar bears cant simply adapt to living on a land based diet. For more detail on this topic please see: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6eH7Ra6nT-A. The very simple fact is that Polar Bears in the wild rely on sea ice to survive. Also, certainly don't be mislead by thinking the Arctic is void of life. Quite the contrary; it is actually a very complex ecosystem teeming with life! From polar bears, walrus and whales down to the incredibly important plankton, fish and birds. By saying we need to ‚Äòstop climate change‚Äô we are not referring to longer-term natural cycles, but the proven changes and damage we are causing right now. By greatly reducing our rampant greenhouse gas emissions we can help stop or even reverse these negative effects on our planet today.
